'''Short Creek Township''' is one of the fifteen [[civil township|townships]] of [[Harrison County, Ohio|Harrison County]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]].  The [[United States Census, 2000|2000 census]] found 1,012 people in the township, 614 of whom lived in the unincorporated portions of the township.<ref>[http://www.osuedc.org/profiles/population/places.php?sid=41&fips=39067 Harrison County, Ohio <U+2014> Population by Places Estimates]  [[Ohio State University]], 2007.  Accessed 15 May 2007.</ref>

==Geography==
Located in the southeastern corner of the county, it borders the following townships:
*[[Green Township, Harrison County, Ohio|Green Township]] - north
*[[Smithfield Township, Jefferson County, Ohio|Smithfield Township, Jefferson County]] - northeast
*[[Mount Pleasant Township, Jefferson County, Ohio|Mount Pleasant Township, Jefferson County]] - east
*[[Colerain Township, Belmont County, Ohio|Colerain Township, Belmont County]] - southeast corner
*[[Wheeling Township, Belmont County, Ohio|Wheeling Township, Belmont County]] - south
*[[Athens Township, Harrison County, Ohio|Athens Township]] - southwest
*[[Cadiz Township, Harrison County, Ohio|Cadiz Township]] - northwest

Two incorporated villages are located in Short Creek Township: [[Adena, Ohio|Adena]] in the northeast, and [[Harrisville, Ohio|Harrisville]] in the southeast.

==Name and history==
It is the only Short Creek Township statewide.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Detailed map of Ohio| work = | publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]| year = 2000| url = http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/general_ref/cousub_outline/cen2k_pgsz/oh_cosub.pdf| format = PDF| accessdate =2007-02-16}}</ref>

==Government==
The township is governed by a three-member board of trustees, who are elected in November of odd-numbered years to a four-year term beginning on the following January 1. Two are elected in the year after the presidential election and one is elected in the year before it. There is also an elected township fiscal officer,<ref>[http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/503.24 <U+00A7>503.24], [http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/505.01 <U+00A7>505.01], and [http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/507.01 <U+00A7>507.01] of the [[Ohio Revised Code]]. Accessed 4/30/2009.</ref> who serves a four-year term beginning on April 1 of the year after the election, which is held in November of the year before the presidential election. Vacancies in the fiscal officership or on the board of trustees are filled by the remaining trustees.

